# 11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> "The key observation is that a new adjacent `'11'` pair is created only when I place a `1` immediately after another `1`. Therefore, my DP state keeps three pieces of information: the current position, how many adjacent pairs have been formed so far, and the previous bit. The memoized solution runs in `O(n × k)` time. Since each position only depends on the previous position, I can optimize the space to `O(k)` using a rolling DP array while keeping the same time complexity."

